WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.714 --> 00:00:04.380
ELLIE POWERS: So I'm
going to talk today

00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:07.020
about getting the
most from Google Play.

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:09.060
My name is Ellie Powers.

00:00:09.060 --> 00:00:11.960
I'm a product manager
on the Google Play team.

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:14.330
And I work on apps.

00:00:14.330 --> 00:00:17.640
Many of you are here
building apps, but why?

00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:18.190
Right?

00:00:18.190 --> 00:00:19.529
Why are we doing this?

00:00:19.529 --> 00:00:21.070
Well, for some of
us, it's because we

00:00:21.070 --> 00:00:23.610
have a particular idea that
we're really passionate about,

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.390
and we want to get
out into the world.

00:00:25.390 --> 00:00:26.890
For some of us,
it's because we have

00:00:26.890 --> 00:00:28.760
an idea for an exciting
new business that

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:30.480
doesn't exist yet.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:32.560
And the sort of world
that we're talking about

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:35.580
is this multi-device,
multi-billion person world

00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:39.250
that's grown over the
past decade or so.

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:42.460
And we're also going to talk
about how Google, specifically

00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:44.320
Google Play, is
uniquely positioned

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:46.890
to help you get your idea
and your business out

00:00:46.890 --> 00:00:50.180
into the world and as
successful as possible.

00:00:50.180 --> 00:00:51.770
So first a little bit about me.

00:00:51.770 --> 00:00:52.560
I love to travel.

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:54.510
I've been to countries
all over the world.

00:00:54.510 --> 00:00:55.984
And my favorite
thing when I travel

00:00:55.984 --> 00:00:57.650
is to go to a place
that's going to make

00:00:57.650 --> 00:01:00.540
me feel a little bit
out of my element.

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:02.220
The other reason
I love to travel

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:03.709
is they tell me
that it's supposed

00:01:03.709 --> 00:01:06.250
to be a really good idea to get
away from your work from time

00:01:06.250 --> 00:01:07.070
to time.

00:01:07.070 --> 00:01:09.260
But unfortunately, when
you work on mobile apps,

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:11.440
this is getting really
hard to do actually.

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:16.040
So about a year ago, I went on
a trip to Thailand and Cambodia.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:18.750
And when I was on the subways
in Thailand thinking-- yeah,

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:22.460
I'll get away from my work-- I'm
seeing ads for Android games.

00:01:22.460 --> 00:01:24.230
And then I go to the
markets in Cambodia

00:01:24.230 --> 00:01:26.500
and I see Android
devices for sale.

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:29.220
And it's really a nice reminder
that the work that we're

00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:32.080
doing here, to build this
mobile ecosystem together,

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:34.800
is really reaching people
all over the world.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:37.270
And today here we are
in Moscone Center,

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:39.220
and we're seeing that
the wave of Android

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:41.090
is now going in both directions.

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:42.830
Not only are our
users everywhere,

00:01:42.830 --> 00:01:45.450
but there are developers
all over the globe.

00:01:45.450 --> 00:01:47.440
Just actually across
here on the floor here,

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:49.790
we have a developer
called Rayark, also

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:51.200
from Southeast Asia.

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:53.977
And they've made a beautiful,
immersive game experience.

00:01:53.977 --> 00:01:55.810
And if you haven't seen
it yet, I definitely

00:01:55.810 --> 00:01:58.400
recommend that you go and
check it out afterwards.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:01.200
So these are the sorts of
strong mobile ecosystems

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:03.090
that we're building
all around the world

00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:05.830
and they're tied together
through Google Play.

00:02:05.830 --> 00:02:09.139
So how did Google get involved
in this whole mobile apps

00:02:09.139 --> 00:02:09.690
thing?

00:02:09.690 --> 00:02:12.410
Let's go a little bit further
back into Google's history.

00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:16.730
So my first experience
with Google was this box.

00:02:16.730 --> 00:02:18.900
And you could just
type stuff into the box

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:20.730
and it would just
find things for you.

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:21.646
It was magic.

00:02:21.646 --> 00:02:23.770
And this was the first
opportunity that a lot of us

00:02:23.770 --> 00:02:26.650
had to see just how
big the world was,

00:02:26.650 --> 00:02:29.380
and that seemingly far
away ideas and places

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:31.640
were now becoming within reach.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:33.700
And so this was what
Google started out with,

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:36.270
connecting people with the
information and the products

00:02:36.270 --> 00:02:38.330
that they were interested in.

00:02:38.330 --> 00:02:39.280
So what happened next?

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:42.700
Well, on April 1,
2004, Gmail launched.

00:02:42.700 --> 00:02:45.880
In 2005, YouTube joined Google.

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:47.780
And then with maps and
other key launches,

00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:50.840
Google became known for
customer-centric internet

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:53.941
experiences and really,
really enormous scale.

00:02:53.941 --> 00:02:55.440
I mean, you may
have remembered what

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:57.850
a big deal it was
over 10 years ago

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:00.680
when you finally got a whole
gigabyte for your online email

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:04.190
where people were offering
just a fraction of that.

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:05.690
And this meant that
your information

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:07.450
could be truly
accessible from anywhere.

00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:09.630
And this was
happening on the web.

00:03:09.630 --> 00:03:12.102
It was happening on
desktop computers.

00:03:12.102 --> 00:03:13.810
Maybe you remember
having a dial-up modem

00:03:13.810 --> 00:03:15.340
and that big upgrade
moment to DSL.

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:17.440
And this was cool and exciting.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:19.510
And let's fast forward to today.

00:03:19.510 --> 00:03:22.440
Well, Android had
joined back in 2005.

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:24.834
What's happened in
those almost 10 years

00:03:24.834 --> 00:03:26.750
is that we've now moved
on to the next chapter

00:03:26.750 --> 00:03:27.620
of the internet.

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:29.720
We have billions of
people connecting.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.780
Many of them are using
Android as their first device.

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:33.980
And what happens?

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:36.150
What is the difference
between your desktop computer

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:39.190
and a website with your
mobile device today?

00:03:39.190 --> 00:03:42.030
You're now in this kind of
loop of constant interaction.

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:44.280
You've replaced
clicking and typing

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:48.762
with touch screens, voice
controls, and sensors.

00:03:48.762 --> 00:03:50.720
And Google's still doing
what Google has always

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:52.950
done best which is
connecting people

00:03:52.950 --> 00:03:54.400
with the information
and products

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:56.140
that they find most interesting.

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:59.460
What this means here is now
connecting people with the apps

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.150
that they love on
a range of devices.

00:04:02.150 --> 00:04:05.240
So what we're going
to do today is

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:09.040
talk about what this means
to developers like all of us.

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:11.280
So again, why do we develop?

00:04:11.280 --> 00:04:12.365
Why do we build apps?

00:04:12.365 --> 00:04:15.370
It's to get our ideas and
businesses out into the world.

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:17.019
And an app is
definitely the best way

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:18.950
to do that in this day and age.

00:04:18.950 --> 00:04:20.610
So what we're going
to talk about today

00:04:20.610 --> 00:04:24.506
is how your app can reach the
right users at the right time,

00:04:24.506 --> 00:04:25.880
and the approach
that you'll take

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:28.920
is going to depend on
what stage your app is in.

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:30.420
So first, I want
to talk to those

00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:32.370
of you who are just
getting started.

00:04:32.370 --> 00:04:35.194
Maybe you've just built an app
or you have an idea for one.

00:04:35.194 --> 00:04:36.860
You don't have any
users yet, so that'll

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:38.310
be your first challenge.

00:04:38.310 --> 00:04:40.821
So before you publish
your app, you probably

00:04:40.821 --> 00:04:43.070
want to understand this
ecosystem that you're joining,

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:44.960
and that's Google Play.

00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:46.370
So what is Play?

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:51.220
Play is an ecosystem of apps,
developers, and the store.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:55.080
We have the one billion devices
that were discussed before

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:56.440
and the people who use them.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:58.550
Well over a million
apps are in the store.

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:00.230
And behind the scenes,
we have massively

00:05:00.230 --> 00:05:01.930
scaled cloud computing
services that

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:04.930
can help to do everything that
we're going to talk about next.

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:08.130
What I think about what Google
Play really is at its core

00:05:08.130 --> 00:05:09.720
is a matchmaker.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:12.810
If I'm a user, it's going to try
to match me with a sort of app

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:14.002
that I'm going to want.

00:05:14.002 --> 00:05:16.210
Maybe I'm looking for that
app, or maybe I don't even

00:05:16.210 --> 00:05:18.709
know I'm looking and it's just
helping me discover something

00:05:18.709 --> 00:05:20.276
new about what my device can do.

00:05:20.276 --> 00:05:22.150
And then on the other
side, if I have an app,

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:24.180
it's going to match me
with the sort of users

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:26.640
who are going to be
interested in my app.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.836
So let's start out
with something new,

00:05:28.836 --> 00:05:30.460
something that's
coming soon, something

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:33.640
that we're incredibly
excited about.

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:35.790
So earlier in the keynote,
you heard the discussion

00:05:35.790 --> 00:05:38.190
about material design.

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:39.990
And on Play we're
really trying to take

00:05:39.990 --> 00:05:42.910
this beautiful, interactive
layout to heart.

00:05:42.910 --> 00:05:44.910
Now, when you launch a
new app and you put it up

00:05:44.910 --> 00:05:46.820
on the Play store,
you really want

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:49.840
to make a great
first impression.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.130
So we've decided to
make the store listing

00:05:52.130 --> 00:05:54.540
on Google Play even
more appealing.

00:05:54.540 --> 00:05:56.690
And by the way, this is
just a general concept.

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:59.047
It's not totally
done, but we wanted

00:05:59.047 --> 00:06:01.130
to share with you early
so that you can understand

00:06:01.130 --> 00:06:03.640
the context in which your
app will be available.

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:07.120
So at the top you can see this
beautiful feature graphic.

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:09.830
And at the bottom you can
see a quick text summary

00:06:09.830 --> 00:06:12.820
where you can explain to users
exactly what your app will

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:13.900
for them.

00:06:13.900 --> 00:06:17.470
So you might want to go
into the Developer Console

00:06:17.470 --> 00:06:19.650
and make sure that you
actually have this graphic

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:22.380
and text available so that
when we roll this out,

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:24.060
your app will be ready.

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:25.560
And in the middle
here, you're going

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:28.660
to see the reasons why the user
may want to install the app.

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:31.150
So for example, a great
reason to install the app

00:06:31.150 --> 00:06:32.860
is it's got a high star rating.

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:34.360
So we call that
out really clearly.

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:36.520
Or maybe it's got
a lot of downloads.

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:39.180
Or maybe, it's
because your friend

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:41.630
has installed it and
given it a high rating.

00:06:41.630 --> 00:06:43.560
So this is going to
be rolling out soon,

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:46.080
and we hope that it'll help you
make your apps give a better

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:48.120
first impression.

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:49.230
OK.

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:52.350
When I go out in the world and
actually talk to Android users,

00:06:52.350 --> 00:06:55.330
I like to ask them how they
find about their favorite apps.

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:58.264
The number one reason I hear
again and again is-- well,

00:06:58.264 --> 00:07:00.430
I found this app because
my friend told me about it.

00:07:00.430 --> 00:07:01.810
Perfectly natural.

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:03.670
And that's why on
Google Play we're

00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:05.360
trying to reflect
the same behavior.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:09.270
Whenever we see that your friend
has rated or plus-oned an app,

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:10.970
we tell you about it.

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:13.654
And we also show you why we
make each [? introduction. ?]

00:07:13.654 --> 00:07:15.070
We don't just say
install the app.

00:07:15.070 --> 00:07:18.570
We say you should
install this app because.

00:07:18.570 --> 00:07:20.840
So what this does is it
creates a ripple effect.

00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:23.150
If you find one user
who installs your app

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:25.050
and gives you a
rating of plus 1,

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:27.470
it'll ripple out to effect
all of their friends

00:07:27.470 --> 00:07:29.930
and build more momentum
behind your app.

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:31.650
You can also now
follow top brands

00:07:31.650 --> 00:07:36.420
like Wired or the New
Yorker, or even celebrities.

00:07:36.420 --> 00:07:38.930
So we talked about Play
being a matchmaker.

00:07:38.930 --> 00:07:39.800
How do we do this?

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.810
We're using the
full power of Google

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:43.270
and the user's
full profile to be

00:07:43.270 --> 00:07:45.640
able to target the right
app to the right user

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:46.890
at the right time.

00:07:46.890 --> 00:07:48.790
We've also created
these targeted groups

00:07:48.790 --> 00:07:50.570
of apps based on user interests.

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:52.900
So here, you can
see racing games

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:55.080
and you can also see
food and drink apps.

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:57.970
And we don't necessarily show
these groups to everybody, only

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.290
to the people who we know
have these interests.

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.150
We also show personalized
recommendations

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:04.085
that are based on a
whole variety of things

00:08:04.085 --> 00:08:05.460
we know about the
user, including

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:08.470
what their friends
have recommended.

00:08:08.470 --> 00:08:10.160
And Play Games is
something that's

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:14.240
really helpful for those of
you who are making game apps.

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:15.770
Play Game Services
are a great way

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:18.660
to enhance your app, to make
it more social and more fun.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.310
We launched it last
year at I/O, and we've

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:24.690
heard that it's a great
way to discover more games

00:08:24.690 --> 00:08:26.430
and also to engage
with the games

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:27.850
that you're already playing.

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:30.800
So today at I/O we announced
some really exciting features,

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:33.980
including the new user profile,
which you can see here.

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:36.470
It's showing which games you
play in the achievements.

00:08:36.470 --> 00:08:38.390
For example, on the
screenshot behind me

00:08:38.390 --> 00:08:40.159
you can see how many
experience points

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:42.380
that this particular
user has accumulated

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:44.000
in different types of games.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:45.910
And then you can
also create what

00:08:45.910 --> 00:08:47.637
are called quests
inside your app.

00:08:47.637 --> 00:08:49.970
You can say-- hey, user, why
don't you go and accomplish

00:08:49.970 --> 00:08:52.630
this particular objective
in a limited time.

00:08:52.630 --> 00:08:55.970
And then we'll also go and show
those quests in the Play Games

00:08:55.970 --> 00:08:59.230
app to help recruit new users.

00:08:59.230 --> 00:09:02.520
So if a user is looking for
your app, if you're a developer,

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:04.610
you want to be absolutely
sure that that user will

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:06.830
find that app no matter
where they're looking.

00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:10.070
And so that's why it's
integrated with Google Search.

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:12.610
So if someone is on an
Android device and searches

00:09:12.610 --> 00:09:14.420
for your app in
Google Search that

00:09:14.420 --> 00:09:17.620
could be in Chrome or maybe
in the Google search app,

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:20.430
will actually show your
apps in the search results

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:22.430
in a nice way with an
easy install button

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:26.207
so they can install the
app directly from there.

00:09:26.207 --> 00:09:28.540
And then a new feature that
we're rolling out this year,

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:29.956
and we're very
happy to say is now

00:09:29.956 --> 00:09:33.310
available to all
developers, is app indexing.

00:09:33.310 --> 00:09:36.110
So you're probably familiar
with the idea of Google indexing

00:09:36.110 --> 00:09:39.380
websites, but actually, Google
can do basically the same thing

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:40.740
with apps too.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:42.850
So what does this
allow us to do?

00:09:42.850 --> 00:09:45.620
It can allow us to link a
search with a particular page

00:09:45.620 --> 00:09:48.740
inside an app that a user
already has in your device.

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:49.810
So let's give an example.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.310
So here, the user
is saying-- I want

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:53.924
to search for a Chromecast,
where can I buy it?

00:09:53.924 --> 00:09:55.340
And it turns out
this user already

00:09:55.340 --> 00:09:56.670
had the Walmart app installed.

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:58.330
So when they click
on the link, it'll

00:09:58.330 --> 00:10:00.890
actually launch the
Chromecast app-- sorry,

00:10:00.890 --> 00:10:02.360
launch the Walmart
app-- directly

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:03.517
to the Chromecast page.

00:10:03.517 --> 00:10:05.350
And so this means that
we're giving the user

00:10:05.350 --> 00:10:08.190
the best possible
experience on their device.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:10.270
So if you're interested
in trying this out now,

00:10:10.270 --> 00:10:12.500
this will be available
in the developer console

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:14.000
through a special
link where you can

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.380
link your app to your website.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:16.880
OK.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:20.340
So that's how Play can
act as a matchmaker.

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:23.060
And you publish your app,
and a lot of this goodness

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:24.910
just happens for
you automatically.

